Though colotomie and colotomisch were used by him in De toonkunst van Java (vol. 1, Nijhoff, 1934, p. 232 passim), the noun was introduced earlier by the Dutch-Austrian musician and writer Linda Bandara (pseudonym of Sieglinde Hofland, 1881-1955), in “Über javanische Musik,” Die Musik, Band 38, 10. Jahrgang, 2. Quartalsband (1910-11), pp. 341-46 (later translated by the author into Dutch, in Weekblad voor Indië, 16de Jaargang, No. 33, 23 November, 1919, pp. 482-83). Middle English bombard, bumbard, borrowed from Middle French bombarde, probably from an onomatopoeic base bomb- + -arde -ard  — more at 1bomb  ◆As with bomba, bombe, etc. (see 1bomb), the origin and diffusion of bombarda, bombarde, etc., remain incompletely elucidated. French bombarde, in reference to an engine of war, appears in the Vrayes chroniques of Jean le Bel, a history of the Hundred Years War begun in 1357 (see Dictionnaire du Moyen Français, on line) and in the accounts of the Valenciennes city clerk Nicole de Dury from 1363 (see H. Caffiaux, Nicole de Dury, maître clerc de la ville de Valenciennes 1361-1373, Valenciennes, 1866, p. 103). Italian bombarda may be dependent on the French word, given that the earliest use of the word is in reference to artillery used at the battle of Crécy in 1346 (in the final book of the Nuova Cronica of Giovanni Villani, who died in 1348; manuscripts containing the final book are significantly later). The 1311 date given for bombarda in Trésor de la langue française, Cortelazzo and Zolli’s Dizionario etimologico della lingua italiana, and a number of earlier sources from which they draw (as the Enciclopedia Italiana) is incorrect; the text in question, the Polystorio or Polyhistoria by Niccolò da Ferrara (not Bartolomeo da Ferrara), alludes to events of 1311 but was written sometime after 1367, when the chronicle ends, at the court of Niccolò II d’Este, marquess of Ferrara from 1361 (cf. Richard Tristano, “History ‘Without Scruple’: The Enlightenment Confronts the Middle Ages in Renaissance Ferrara,” Medievalia et Humanistica, new series, no. 38 [2012], p. 85). Spanish lombarda, attested about 1400, is clearly a folk-etymologizing of bombarda (pace Coromines’ etymology in Diccionario crítico-etimológico castellano e hispánico, which does not take account of the earlier French forms). Bombarde in reference to a musical instrument is perhaps an independent formation. The earliest occurrence appears to be the French form bombares (plural), an item in a list of musical instruments in the Livre des Mestiers, a 14th-century French-Flemish conversation manual; the corresponding Middle Dutch form in the text is bombaren (see Jean Gessler, editor, Le Livre des Mestiers de Bruges et ses dérivés: quatres anciens manuels de conversation, Bruges, 1931; Gessler dates the text to ca. 1340, but a later study avers that the list of coins in the text demand a terminus post quem of 1367—cf. Philip Grierson, “The Date of the ‘Livre des Mestiers’ and Its Derivatives,” Revue belge de philologie et d’historie, vol. 35 [1957], pp. 778-83). Anglo-French bombard can be dated more exactly, to a list of wind instruments of 1391-92 in the records of the London goldsmiths’ guild (see Lisa Jefferson, editor, Wardens’ Accounts and Court Minute Books of the Goldsmiths’ Mistery of London, 1334-1446, Boydell Press, 2003, p. 236). The alleged Medieval Latin form bombarda (in the ablative plural bombardis), which the Mittellateinisches Wörterbuch attributes to the Trotula medical texts composed in 12th-century Salerno, is a late corruption taken from the first printed edition of Trotula (J. Schott, Strasbourg, 1544); the manuscript tradition has Lombardis in this passage (see Monica H. Green, The Trotula: An English Translation of the Medieval Compendium of Women’s Medicine, Philadelphia, 2001, pp. 55, 83, 189).First Known Use: 15th century (sense 1)

Middle English barayl, barel, borrowed from Anglo-French barel, baril (continental Old French barril), going back to Gallo-Romance *barrīculus, probably diminutive of *barrīca “cask, barrel”  — more at 2barricade  ◆The Gallo-Romance ancestor of Old French barril is attested as barriclos (accusative plural) in the Capitulare de Villis, a Carolingian manual for royal estate management that survives in a single manuscript of about 800, nearly contemporary with its composition (“Volumus ut bonos barriclos ferro ligatos, quos in hostem et ad palatium mittere possint, iudices singuli praeparatos semper habeant, et buttes ex coriis non faciant” - “We desire that the various stewards should always have by them good barrels bound with iron, which they can send to the army or to the palace, and that they should not make leather wineskins”). It is striking that if this word is a diminutive of *barrīca, it is attested significantly earlier (see supplemental note at 2barricade). The Capitulare de Villis is thought to have been composed in Aquitaine (at this period roughly France south of the river Loire). If the word did in fact originate in this area, it had spread to Catalonia by the tenth century, where it is found in Latin documents as barrile and barrilo (see references at barril in Joan Coromines, Diccionari etimològic i complementari de la llengua catalana, vol. 1 (Barcelona, 1983). The word appears in several vernaculars in succeeding centuries, presumably diffused from an Aquitanian/Catalonian nucleus.First Known Use: 14th century (sense 1)

borrowed from Portuguese, borrowed from Arabic aṭ-ṭabaq, from aṭ, assimilated form of al, definite article + ṭabaq “lid, plate, shallow bowl, tray” ◆The sense “drum” of the Portuguese word contrasts not only with the Arabic etymon, but with the meaning elsewhere in Iberian Romance. Spanish tabaque appears in older dictionaries as a kind of basket (glossed cestillo o canastillo pequeño de mimbres, que regularmente sirve para traher su labor las mugeres, y tenerla à mano, “little wicker basket, which women regularly use to carry their work, holding it by the hand,” in the Diccionario de Autoridades of the Real Academia Española, 1739); the word in approximately this sense is attested from the 14th century (for details see Juan Corominas, Diccionario crítico etimológico castellano e hispánico). The “basket” meaning is actually assigned to the Arabic word ṭbaq (= canistrum, calathum) in the 12th-century Latin-Arabic glossary, probably produced in Toledo, in the library of Leiden University. The path by which “lid” or “basket” became “drum” in Portuguese is not clear. Early occurrences of atabaque (first attested as atauaque in the 14th-century Livro de Linhagens do Conde Dom Pedro) tend to be within enumerations of musical instruments (North African, sub-Saharan, or Asian) that are otherwise not defined, so that it is possible that atabaque originally denoted some sort of cymbal or tambourine. However, the following passage from the Peregrinação of Fernão Mendes Pinto (written before the author’s death in 1583, though not printed till 1614) appears to refer to a drum: “ … oito homẽs & cinco molheres … bailando todos ao som de hum atabaque em que de quando em quando dauão cinco pancadas, & dando outras tantas palmadas com as mãos, dezião alto & muyto desentoado, cur cur hinau falem” (“ … eight men and five women … all dancing to the sound of an atabaque, on which they beat five strokes from time to time, and as many times clapping their hands, they uttered loudly and very discordantly ‘cur cur hinau falem’.”) (Pinto was somewhere on the shores of the South China Sea at the time.)First Known Use: 1824
